Lots of life happening over here. I’ll be 36 weeks pregnant this week - welcoming baby boy #2 SO SOON!!! Until then, I’ll be soaking in this sweet time with my core people, resting as much as humanly possible while being full time with a very lively 2.5 year old boy 😂 & renovating our house. Again, lots of life happening over here but the Lord is teaching me a lot in this season. 🫶🏼 also, I’m just excited I must say because @hudbuckets blesses me with the cutest kids. I can’t wait to see what baby C (that’s a hint 😉) looks like!!

Embracing these final days of pregnancy with so much excitement & anticipation. In so many ways, I know exactly what to expect, but there is still a sense of mystery. When will he make his debut? What will it feel like to be a mom of three? 🥹 How will this change our family dynamic? Will this really be my last pregnancy? These are all questions I keep asking myself.. 

All questions aside, with each pregnancy, I feel immensely grateful. Creating life from love & having the opportunity to watch & feel it grow inside me is a blessing. & with that, I say thank you, Lord, for choosing me to steward the life of this precious baby. I can’t wait to meet him, but until then I’m cherishing every kick, every flutter & growing pain because I know this very well might be the last time I get to experience this. 

Also, a huge thank you to my sweet & dear friend @gracecobbphoto who has now captured two epic milestones in our journey. She is amazing. I was on the fence about doing maternity photos but I’m so happy I did!! 🥹🫶🏼

Candor Nicholas Brock, the sweetest boy, made his way into the world on 3/3/23 at 6:37 PM. He came amidst the storm & has been the most perfect addition to our family. 

“Candor” - a quality of being honest; an openness of the heart. Originally inspired by my grandmother, “Candida,” aka “grandma Candy.” 

“Nicholas,” - victory of the people. Inspired by my brother, who was indeed a man of candor & a true rock in my life. 

It feels really special to be able to honor the legacy of my family through the name of this baby. I pray, like those of his namesake, that he will be a man of candor & that his presence will radiate the light of Jesus, bringing forth the ultimate victory of the people. 🫶🏼 

My heart is so full!! I love you @hudbuckets & this family we’ve created.
I can’t wait to show him this video one day. Baby Candor, you are so loved. 🥹

Garlic & Rosemary Focaccia bread ✨🫶🏼 

I am a bread making amateur BUT this recipe was easy & delicious!! Found on Pinterest at @gimmesomeoven with a few modifications. 💛

Ingredients needed:

- 1 1/3 cup warm water 
- 2 teaspoons sugar or honey (I used sugar)
- 1 (0.25 ounce) package active-dry yeast
- 3 1/2 cups all purpose flour + more as needed
- 1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil + more for drizzling
- 2 teaspoons flaky sea salt, + more for sprinkling*
- 2 sprigs fresh rosemary, chopped
- 2 - 3 cloves of garlic, minced or chopped 

Mix the sugar in a mixing bowl with the warm water until dissolved then add the yeast & mix again. Wait 5-10 minutes until the yeast is foamy & begin to gradually mix in your flour, oil, salt, & garlic! I would also add some of the rosemary in right here if I made it again - hoping it would add a little more depth of flavor. Mix until the dough is formed & then knead for 5-10 minutes (adding extra flour if too sticky). I kneaded my dough by hand, but you could use your stand mixer if you have a bread hook! Once the dough is ready, transfer to a greased bowl & cover. Let rise for 1 hour. Contrary to what you see in this video - transfer the dough to a greased sheet pan or 9x13 baking dish (not the counter) to spread out to 1/2 inch consistency. Cover & let rise a second time for 20-30 minutes. (I wish I had done this so the bread didn’t deflate as much after the transfer of the second proof). Preheat your oven to 400 degrees F. Once the bread has risen for the second time, use your fingers to press into the bread all the way to the bottom of the pan / baking sheet. Top with a drizzle of oil, fresh rosemary & flakey salt. Bake for 20 minutes or until top of dough is golden brown. I drizzled mine with oil once more after baked! So good. So yummy!!
